  "response_text": "A stage curtain fills the background, lit by a round spotlight that moves across the floor and drapery. In the light stands a small sign on an easel with decorative edging. The sign reads “DON WILSON presents Derusto.” A heavyset, balding older man in a dark suit, white shirt, and dark tie steps out from behind the sign. He carries a small can in one hand. Another person remains mostly hidden behind the curtain and the easel; only an arm reaches out from the right, as if handing or presenting something to him. The man moves into the center of the spotlight, smiling and facing forward like a stage host, while holding up the can for the audience to see.\n\nHe stands alone against the curtain, framed by the bright circular spotlight, and raises the product near his shoulder. The can is small and cylindrical, with a bold label. He gestures toward it, first holding it at chest height and then pointing at the label with one finger. As he brings it closer, the label becomes readable: “Mint-Finish Derusto” with “dries in minutes.” Another band of text on the lower part of the label reads “prevents rust – stops rust” and “24 beautiful colors.” He continues to point to different parts of the can, turning it slightly in his hands so the front label faces outward.\n\nThe product is then shown in close-up, filling most of the view while the man’s hands hold it steady. His finger taps or points to the lower label where the rust-prevention claim is printed. The can’s rim and lid are visible at the top, and the large “Derusto” name dominates the center. The black-and-white image cannot show the actual paint colors, but the printed label emphasizes that the product comes in multiple decorator colors.\n\nThe scene shifts into practical demonstrations of the paint being applied to metal. A hand uses a brush on a decorative metal railing with curled scrollwork in front of a door, coating the horizontal rail and nearby bars. Another example shows a hand holding a Derusto spray can beneath a metal chair or patio furniture frame, aiming the nozzle at the underside where metal tubes meet the seat. The product is also applied with a paint roller to a chain-link fence; the roller moves across the diamond-patterned wire, leaving a lighter painted section as it passes. These brief examples visually match the idea that Derusto can be brushed, sprayed, or rolled onto metal surfaces.\n\nThe commercial returns to the man on the stage holding the can. He again presents it toward the audience, then a close view of the can reappears with the same visible wording: “Mint-Finish Derusto,” “dries in minutes,” “prevents rust – stops rust,” and “24 beautiful colors.” He points once more to the lower label.\n\nBack on the curtained stage, the man stands in the spotlight with the can in his hands. A separate arm appears from behind the curtain holding out a broad paintbrush above the “Don Wilson” sign, as though offering him a tool. The man turns toward it, and soon he is shown holding both the can and the wide brush, smiling as he faces forward. He then walks toward a large product display at the side of the stage.\n\nThe display is a store-style rack filled with many rows of Derusto cans, arranged in neat horizontal lines. Behind the cans is a large sign that reads “RUST PREVENTION HEADQUARTERS.” The sign features a smiling woman’s face in the center, with product images on either side, including a can and what appears to be a spray version. Smaller circular graphics around the sign suggest different household or metal-use examples. The man stands beside the display holding the can and brush, turning slightly toward the audience.\n\nThe final images focus on the display and then on a single large Derusto can. The display sign with “RUST PREVENTION HEADQUARTERS” remains visible behind rows of cans. A final close-up isolates one can on a plain surface, with the label facing forward: “Mint-Finish Derusto,” “dries in minutes,” “prevents rust – stops r